Zimbabwe has added 300MW to its national power grid. President Emmerson Mnangagwa flagged off two generators from China’s Sinohydro Corp that will produce 150MW each at Kariba, the country’s largest hydropower plant 360 km North of the capital Harare. According to the president, work to expand the coal-fired Hwange plant by 600 MW will start soon especially now that financing had been secured from Chinese investors. In the previous years, Zimbabwe has been struggling to produce enough electricity due to ageing equipment, The most recent power plant having been built in 1987. It produces 1,200 MW against a demand of 1,600 MW. The balance is imported from Mozambique and South Africa. Also read:EU commits US $25m to solar projects in Africa Sinohydro Corp will also carry out the Hwange expansion. According to Mnangagwa the Hwange expansion project has reached financial closure and work will commence soon. Chinese President Xi Jinping, signed a deal for the Hwange plant, valued at more than US $1bn, in 2015 but had stalled under the rule of Robert Mugabe. Mnangagwa said he will soon visit Beijing, where he is going to seek loans to help revive the economy of Zimbabwe. Zimbabwe, has over the years turned to China for investment to help an economy desperate for new infrastructure like roads, power and water.